<h2><i class="mch-book-open"></i> 9.2.1 PROFICIENCY</h2>
<div class="evidenceBorder">
  <h3><i class="mch-search"></i> <img src="../../images/smart-1-1-magnifying-glass.jpg" alt="Image of Magnifying Glass" class="right ppic" />REVIEW. The Competency in Detail</h3>
  <p>The following drop-downs contain information on each of the knowledge areas and skills needed to implement the competency. <strong>Please explore the content below.</strong></p>
  <h3><strong>Teaching, Coaching and Mentoring</strong></h3>
  <p><strong>Knowledge Areas. </strong>MCH leaders will demonstrate a working knowledge of:</p>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-book"></i> <strong>9K1.</strong> Teaching strategies.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p><strong>Teaching Strategies</strong><sup>1</sup></p>
    <p>Several strategies are generally useful when teaching and can accommodate a variety of student learning needs. Each strategy is followed by suggestions for implementing it:</p>
    <p><strong>Give students opportunities to think and talk about the subject</strong>.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Lengthen one's &ldquo;wait time&rdquo; after posing a question to the class, ideally to three to five seconds, allowing  students with different thinking styles the chance to speak.</li>
      <li>Replace wait time with the requirement that students write out one to three initial thoughts on how to answer the question.</li>
      <li>Use &ldquo;Think–Pair–Share,&rdquo; where students must think about or write their response to a question, pair with another student to discuss, and then share the results of their discussion.</li>
      <li>Prioritize classroom time to focus on concepts that are most difficult to learn or are critical fundamentals, and consider addressing more straightforward concepts through active learning experiences assigned as homework or pre-class preparation.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Encourage, require, and actively manage the participation of all students</strong>.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Require that students raise their hands before answering a question. Graciously manage discussion dynamics by asking for responses from &ldquo;those who have not yet raised their hands.&rdquo;</li>
      <li>To avoid having to call on the same student/s again and again, ask for a certain number of hands to be raised before selecting a student to respond. If that number of hands isn&rsquo;t raised, then ask students to pair up and write responses to share.</li>
      <li>Ask each student to write their name on a notecard or popsicle stick that you then collect and use to randomly select a student to answer questions you pose during class. Reinforce that class participation isn&rsquo;t punishment but rather the opportunity to hear from a variety of voices.</li>
      <li>Assign a &ldquo;reporter&rdquo; for small-group discussions, and ensure that this duty is rotated fairly among all students.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Build a welcoming and balanced classroom community for all students</strong>.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Learn students&rsquo; names, or distribute nametags or placecards for students to write their names on.</li>
      <li>Represent various perspectives and backgrounds in lessons and examples.</li>
      <li>Have students work together at stations or in small groups, usually of three to four students, ideally on projects that require all group members to participate.</li>
      <li>Use a variety of active-learning strategies from class session to class session to build a welcoming and balanced learning environment for a wide range of students with different approaches to learning.</li>
      <li>Be direct with students that access, fairness, and classroom equity is a key goal.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Monitor behavior to cultivate different thinking styles</strong>.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Use praise with caution, so other students feel that they still have something to add and can be successful in sharing.</li>
      <li>Use open-ended questions to frame class discussions and or as homework for students to bring to class.</li>
      <li>Do not judge student responses. Acknowledge all responses, even incorrect ones, as neutrally as possible to create a safe environment that encourages students to share all of their ideas.</li>
      <li>Establish a set of accepted usual, typical, standard acceptable behaviors in the classroom.</li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Teach <em>all </em>of the students in your classroom</strong>.</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Students learn from everything going on in the classroom, not just about the subject matter. They begin to take in details about the environment of the classroom from the moment they enter the room.</li>
      <li>Collect assessment information frequently for each and every student, not just those who speak up in class a lot.    </li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Teaching Techniques</strong><sup>2</sup></p>
    <p><strong>Case Studies, Role-playing, and Small Group Discussions: </strong>Participants discover learning points themselves. The individual assumes roles other than his/her real ones or is thrust into settings that are different from the current one. <br>
      Best Use: To practice a newly acquired skill, experience what a particular situation feels like, provide feedback to participants or apply new knowledge to a specific situation, practice problem-solving skills<br>
      Examples: Problem-based learning, psychodramas, sociodramas, group role-play, practice in handling social interactions</p>
    <p><strong>Classroom Training, Lectures, and Lecturettes: </strong>Learners acquire skills and knowledge through guidance from an instructor in a formal group setting. These may be delivered via distance learning, webinars, and webcasts.<br>
      Best Use: To convey information in a short time, to communicate the same information to large numbers of people, or to provide basic information to a group <br>
      Examples: Seminars, conferences, workshops, lectures, demonstrations, Internet-based classes, video and audio conferences, webinars, webcasts,<br>
      certificate programs</p>
    <p><strong>Experiential Learning: </strong>The individual or group participates in structured debriefing sessions to reflect on the experiences encountered and draws conclusions. <br>
      Best Use: In structured and mentored settings<br>
      Examples: Practicum, structured and mentored internship, field placement with coaching, on-the job practice and work sessions, and supervised transitional work settings following training</p>
    <p><strong>Games, Interactive Tabletops, and Simulations:</strong> The individual performs as they would in real life. The setting, however, is an artificial creation designed to resemble the natural environment.<br>
      Best Use: To integrate and apply complex skills, elicit participants&rsquo; natural tendencies 
      and provide feedback, provide a realistic job-related experience, help grasp total program content, present dry material in an interesting way, add a competitive element to a session<br>
      Examples: Physically realistic simulators, virtual-reality environments, psychologically realistic settings, in-basket exercises, structured games, virtual labs, assessment centers</p>
    <p><strong>Projects and Writing Tasks:</strong> Participants reflect on their understanding of concepts, information, ideas and work individually or in small groups to create a written or visual response to a prompt or question.<br>
      Best Use: To test for participants understanding or to provide for individual input<br>
      Examples: Reports, PowerPoint presentations, articles, postings, larger writing projects</p>
    <p><strong>Self-Study:</strong> Participants acquire skills and knowledge through self-learning, guided by structured materials ranging from print to electronic systems.<br>
      Best Use: To enrich classroom lessons, prepare for flipped-classroom lectures, offer more in-depth instructions<br>
      Examples: Directive instruction, computer-based modules, web-based virtual labs, video learning modules, web explorations</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-user"></i> <strong>9K2.</strong> Coaching as a professional relationship.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>According to the International Coaching Federation, coaching is &ldquo;partnering with clients in a thought-provoking and creative process that inspires them to maximize their personal and professional potential.&rdquo;<sup>3</sup></p>
    <p>Coaching involves:<sup>4</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Short, efficient meetings </li>
      <li>Discussions that help clarify situations, offer insights into present work, and suggest areas to improve </li>
      <li>Offering support to improve results in a sustainable way</li>
      <li>Asking quality questions that help a professional discover knowledge they already have and apply what they know to a particular situation</li>
      <li>Customizing a tool or solution for a professional&rsquo;s specific situation</li>
      <li>Personal guidance to help an individual make difficult decisions, step out of a comfort zone, stop destructive behavior, embrace change, or shift performance</li>
      <li>Helping a professional define and then work toward goals</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
      <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-compass3"></i> <strong>9K3.</strong> Mentoring as personal, career-facilitating.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Mentoring is a process in which an experienced individual helps another person develop his or her goals and skills through a series of time-limited, confidential, one-on-one conversations and other learning activities.</p>
    <p>There are four developmental stages of mentoring:<sup>5</sup> </p>
<ol>
  <li>      <strong>Build the relationship</strong>
<ul>
  <li>Get to know each other and begin to establish trust.</li>
      <li>Meet, ideally face-to-face, and discuss your backgrounds, experiences, interests, and expectations. </li>
      <li>Set expectations surrounding confidentiality and the frequency of contact</li>
      <li>Establish a schedule for communicating regularly, whether in-person, by phone, or email.</li>
    </ul>
    </li>
  <li><strong>Exchange information and set goals</strong>
<ul>
  <li>Ascertain the goals your mentee hopes to achieve through the mentoring relationship</li>
      <li>Encourage your mentee to write down these goals</li>
      <li>Refer back to these goals periodically to measure progress and adjust your guidance</li>
      <li>Reinforce that you will not have all the answers, but that you will work with your mentee to help find answers to questions whenever possible</li>
    </ul>
    </li>
  <li><strong>Work toward goals and deepen the engagement</strong>
<ul>
  <li>Help your mentee work toward their goals: have conversations, share written materials, suggest learning and development activities, and introduce them to colleagues.</li>
      <li>Encourage your mentee</li>
      <li>Challenge your mentee to innovate and problem-solve</li>
      <li>Avoid promising more time than you can deliver. Check with your mentee to be certain you are both comfortable with the time you are spending and with what they are learning</li>
  </ul>
    </li>
  <li><strong>End the formal mentoring relationship and plan for the future</strong>
<ul>
  <li>Reflect on accomplishments, challenges, and progress toward goals</li>
      <li>Work with your mentee to define the types of support he or she may need in the future. </li>
      <li>Connect your mentee with colleagues who can provide additional benefits </li>
      <li>Discuss whether the relationship will continue informally</li>
  </ul>
  </li>
  </ol>
    </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-compass3"></i> <strong>9K4.</strong> Teaching, Coaching, Mentoring as a Development Tool.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>At its core, mentoring is a relationship characterized by mutual trust, respect, and a shared commitment to growth. It involves a transfer of knowledge, skills, and experience from the mentor to the mentee, often accompanied by emotional support and guidance.</p>
	<p>Numerous studies have demonstrated the positive impact of mentoring on professional development. Research consistently shows that mentees exhibit higher levels of job satisfaction, career commitment, and organizational citizenship behavior. Additionally, mentoring has been linked to increased earnings, promotions, and career advancement.</p>
	<p>Benefits for the Mentee</p>
	  <ul>
		  <li>Skill development: Mentors provide invaluable insights into industry best practices, problem-solving techniques, and technical expertise. They offer constructive feedback, challenge mentees to step outside their comfort zones, and help them identify areas for improvement.</li>
	      <li>Knowledge transfer: Mentors share their knowledge of organizational networks, and resources. This equips mentees with the tools to navigate their careers effectively and make informed decisions.</li>
	      <li>Career advancement: Mentors offer guidance on career paths, goal-setting, and professional development opportunities. They can help mentees identify their strengths and weaknesses, build their confidence, and develop a strategic career plan.</li>
	      <li>Increased confidence: By providing support, encouragement, and belief in the mentee's potential, mentors contribute to the development of self-confidence and resilience.</li>
	      <li>Networking opportunities: Mentors can introduce mentees to their professional networks, expanding their connections and creating new opportunities for growth.</li>
	  </ul>
	<p>Key Components of Effective Mentoring</p>
	  <ul>
		  <li>Clear goals and expectations: Both mentor and mentee should establish clear objectives for the relationship.</li>
		  <li>Regular communication: Consistent interaction is essential for building trust and maintaining momentum.</li>
		  <li>Active listening: Mentors should actively listen to their mentees' needs and concerns.</li>
		  <li>Feedback and support: Constructive feedback and encouragement are vital for growth.</li>
		  <li>Mutual respect: A foundation of respect is essential for a successful mentoring relationship. </li>
	  </ul>

    </div>   
   
  <p><strong>Skills</strong></p>
  <p><strong><em>Foundational. </em></strong><em>At a foundational level, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
	<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-icon"></i> <strong>9S1.</strong> Develop mentoring/coaching rapport.</button>
  <div class="panel">
	<p>Several core behaviors of mentees and mentors are likely to yield effective mentoring relationships:<sup>6</sup></p>
	 <ul>
	  <li>Align expectations.</li>
	  <li>Build rapport.</li>
	  <li>Maintain open communication.</li>
	  <li>Facilitate mentee agency.</li>
	  <li>Address various factors and be mindful of balance in the mentoring relationship.</li>
	  <li>Adopt practices that include navigating power differentials between mentors and mentees, especially across racial or gender differences.</li>
	  <li>Develop interpersonal comfort, the ability to speak freely and express opinions without repercussion.</li></ul>
    <p>Recognize that the start of a mentorship or coaching relationship will naturally be awkward. There are ways to move through this period and build trust in such relationships:<sup>7</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Give your mentee voice and choice in deciding on activities. Provide a range of activity choices. Let the mentee have control over what you talk about and how you talk about it. </li>
      <li>Be sensitive to your mentee&rsquo;s cues. Don&rsquo;t push them for information or hit them with rapid-fire questioning.</li>
      <li>Respect the trust your mentee places in you. Respond to them in ways that show you see their side of things, giving advice sparingly.</li>
      <li>Allow your mentee to share without fear of getting lectured or judged.</li></ul></div>
  
	<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-list-ordered"></i> <strong>9S2.</strong> Set mentoring/coaching expectations and boundaries.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>It is important to discuss and agree on the appropriate boundaries of the mentoring relationship. Boundaries that are too loose may be misinterpreted, while those that are too rigid can paralyze the relationship.</p>
    <p>Take the time to speak candidly about what each of you expect to give and take in terms of time, as well as how you prefer to interact. Consider the following:<sup>8</sup></p>
<ul>
  <li>Both:
    <ul>
      <li>Talk about your responsibilities, what you can and can&rsquo;t do.</li>
      <li>Agree on frequency, duration and intervals of meetings/communications and how this will occur.</li>
      <li>Beyond agreeing to confidentiality, discuss what confidentiality actually means to each of you in various scenarios.</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
  <li>Mentors:
    <ul>
      <li>What kind of access does the mentee have to you? What is the limit?</li>
      <li>Does being a mentor mean the mentee has unlimited access to you for the duration of the relationship?</li>
      <li>Does communicating require an appointment?</li>
      <li>What kind of telephone access does the mentee have to you?</li>
      <li>What will you do if personal problems crop up? Decide for yourself what issues you are comfortable with, and refer the mentee to the appropriate professionals.</li>
    </ul>
    </li>
  <li>Mentees:
    <ul>
      <li>Avoid unhealthy dependence. For example, mentors are not expected to have definitive answers or be available 24/7.</li>
      <li>Ask yourself &ldquo;What would I do if…&rdquo; in assessing your own boundaries.</li>
      <li>Prioritize how you wish to best utilize your mentor&rsquo;s time and expertise.</li>
      <li>Know what additional resources are available to help you in your career and life.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  </ul>
    </div>
	
	<button class="accordion"><i class="mch-device-desktop"></i> <strong>9S3.</strong>  Use instructional technology tools.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Instructional technologies have been defined as the &ldquo;mindful and purposeful integration of digital technology tools into the teaching and learning process.&rdquo;<sup>9</sup> Technology-enhanced learning environments encourage learners to be active participants in the learning process rather than just passive recipients of knowledge.<sup>10</sup></p>
    <p>Categories of  instructional technologies include:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Blogging</li>
      <li>Wikis</li>
      <li>Video</li>
      <li>Mobile apps</li>
      <li>Online collaborative spaces</li>
      <li>Simulations</li>
    </ul>
    <p>These instructional technologies can all be used to encourage comprehensive participation by combining them in ways that allow synchronous and asynchronous participation. This will help accommodate learners who have varied access to technology and the Internet.<sup>11</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Have students answer and post comments to questions (written by the instructor or by students and curated by the instructor) to a discussion board. Create a plan to monitor the board.</li>
      <li>Promote equity in the remote classroom by allowing students to share their thinking in a variety of ways: give them the option to submit responses or reflections as short videos, audio recordings, or written text. Be prepared to accommodate bandwidth issues students may have.</li>
      <li>Pair students with someone in the class to connect with at least once a week to discuss content or work on an assignment together.</li>
    </ul>
	<p>By selecting and using technology tools thoughtfully, educators can ensure that all students have balanced opportunities to participate and succeed.</p>
	<p>Key strategies for using technology  include:</p>
	  <ul>
		 <li>Accessibility features: Choose tools that offer built-in accessibility features, such as screen readers, closed captioning, and adjustable text size.</li>
	  	 <li>Representation: Look for materials and resources that represent a variety of  backgrounds, and perspectives.</li>
	     <li>Collaborative tools: Utilize collaborative tools that promote teamwork and peer-to-peer learning, allowing students to contribute and learn from each other.</li>
	     <li>Differentiated instruction: Employ technology to provide individualized support and accommodations for students with various learning needs.</li>
	     <li>Digital citizenship: Teach students about responsible digital behavior and online etiquette to create a safe and respectful learning environment.</li></ul>
    <p><a href="https://onlinedegrees.sandiego.edu/instructional-technology-tools/">Explore instructional technologies that can be used to engage students in greater depth</a>.</p>
  </div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-comments-1"></i> <strong>9S4.</strong> Give/receive feedback on behaviors/performance.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Feedback is an important component of a mentor or coaching relationship. It&rsquo;s necessary to learn how to give feedback constructively so that it has some value. Constructive feedback is a tool that is used to build up a person&rsquo;s work situation, not break it down. Delivering feedback constructively allows the other person to know that you are on their side.<sup>9</sup></p>
    <p>Tips for Giving Constructive Feedback<sup>9</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>State the constructive purpose of your feedback: </strong>Indicate what you'd like to cover and why it's important. For those initiating feedback, this focus keeps the other person from having to guess what you want to talk about. When another person requests feedback, a focusing statement makes sure that you direct your feedback toward what the person needs. Examples: &ldquo;I have a concern about,&rdquo; &ldquo;I feel I need to let you know,&rdquo; &ldquo;I want to discuss.&rsquo;</li>
      <li><strong>Describe specifically what you have observed: </strong>Describe an event or action that you have observed personally and be able to say when and where it happened, who was involved, and what the results were. Don&rsquo;t try to speak for others. Avoid vague statements about what a person &ldquo;always&rdquo; or &ldquo;usually&rdquo; does.</li>
      <li><strong>Describe your reactions to a person&rsquo;s behavior: </strong>Explain the consequences of the other person's behavior and give examples of how you and others are affected. When you describe your reactions or the consequences of the observed behaviors, the other person can better appreciate the impact their actions are having on others and on the organization or team as a whole.</li>
      <li><strong>Give the other person an opportunity to respond: </strong>Remain silent and meet the other person's eye, indicating that you are waiting for an answer. If the person hesitates to respond, ask an open ended question, such as: &ldquo;What do you think?&rdquo; &ldquo;What is your view of this situation?&rdquo; &ldquo;What is your reaction to this?&rdquo;</li>
      <li><strong>Offer specific suggestions: </strong>Whenever possible make your suggestions helpful by including practical, feasible examples. Offering suggestions shows that you have thought about how to improve the situation. Even if people are working up to expected standards, they often benefit from ideas that could help them to perform better. If your feedback was offered supportively or neutrally, in the &quot;for your information&quot; mode, or depending on the situation's circumstances, suggestions may not be appropriate. Use your common sense and offer an idea if you think the other person will find it useful. Don't suggest improvement just for the sake of it.</li>
      <li><strong>Summarize and express your support: </strong>Review the major points you discussed. Summarize action items, not the negative points of the other person's behavior. If you have given neutral feedback, emphasize the main points you have wanted to convey. For corrective feedback, stress the main things you've discussed that the person could do differently. End on a positive note by communicating confidence in the person's ability to improve the situation. Summarizing allows you to avoid misunderstandings and check to make sure that your communication is clear. This summary is an opportunity to show your support for the other person, even if you&rsquo;ve had to deliver negative feedback.</li></ul></div>
  <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-speech-streamline-talk-user"></i> <strong>9S5.</strong> Cultivate active listening skills.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Active listening not only establishes rapport but creates a positive, accepting environment that permits open communication. By listening actively, you will understand the interests and needs of the person you&rsquo;re engaging.<sup>5</sup></p>
    <p>Active listening examples:<sup>10</sup></p>
<ul>
  <li>Use attending behaviors to indicate that the speaker has your attention:
<ul>
      <li>Refer to the speaker by name.</li>
      <li>Use encouraging statements, i.e. &ldquo;Uh-huh,&rdquo; &ldquo;Go on,&rdquo; &ldquo;I&rsquo;m listening&rdquo;</li>
      <li>Posture toward the speaker</li>
      <li>Maintain appropriate eye contact</li>
      <li>Display facial expressions that express interest and concern</li>
      <li>Nod head to convey affirmation</li>
      <li>Avoid distractions</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
  <li>Show interest in what they are saying by using a variety of statements intended to confirm, clarify, review or restate the information sent by the speaker and/or the feelings behind the information:
<ul>
      <li>Use clarifying statements to clear up any confusing parts of the speaker&rsquo;s message.</li>
      <li>Use paraphrasing statements to restate the speaker&rsquo;s main ideas.</li>
      <li>Use reflecting statements to focus the speaker&rsquo;s attention on the feelings behind what they are saying.</li>
      <li>Use summarizing statements to pull together ideas the speaker has stated to help focus their thoughts.</li>
      <li>Use body language (such as making eye contact) that shows you are paying attention to what he or she is saying.</li>
      </ul>
    </li>
  <li> If you are talking to them by phone, reduce background noise and limit interruptions. The person you are engaging will feel that he or she has your undivided attention.<sup>5</sup></li>
  <li>Reserve discussing your own experiences or giving advice until after the person you&rsquo;re engaging has had a chance to thoroughly explain his or her issue, question, or concern.<sup>5</sup></li></ul></div>
    
  
  
    
        
    
  <p><em><strong>Advanced.</strong> Building on the foundational skills, MCH leaders will be able to:</em></p>
 
        <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-graph"></i> <strong>9S6. </strong>Evidence-informed education responsive to various needs</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p><span id="docs-internal-guid-cb41dc81-7fff-2c19-5d8d-d31e18bb6296"> Evidence-informed education</span> that is responsive to various needs is everything an instructor does to help students learn. Instructors set aside beliefs and preferences to focus instead on using evidence-informed strategies that have been demonstrated by research to work.</p>
    <p>Examples of evidence-based pedagogy include:<sup>14</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li> State clear learning goals repeatedly, so students have a clear idea of where they are going and what it will look like when they get there. This is a practice that creates transparency in learning and teaching.</li>
      <li>Share and model concepts to explain and then demonstrate how students will perform a task, whether a physical or thinking task. Sharing and modeling looks different in each discipline. For some, that may mean &quot;thinking out loud&quot; to show students how experts process or it may be doing a physical demonstration.</li>
      <li>Check for student understanding by regularly asking for feedback from students in various ways. Research shows that this habit of asking for student feedback has more impact for learning than giving students feedback. You can pick students at random (perhaps using technology or simply slips of paper in a bag) or ask the entire class for a thumbs-up or thumbs-down to indicate whether they understand a concept or not.</li>
      <li>Give feedback to students regularly. Feedback tells students what they did well, where they are now, and how they can improve. Provide feedback in a loop: Think &ldquo;homework,&rdquo; classwork and quizzes. Encourage students to evaluate their own assessment results.</li>
      <li>Summarize new learning in graphical ways for visual learning and deeper processing. Use visuals in presentations (visuals are easier to remember), and create graphs, charts, and Venn diagrams. Have students create their own.</li>
      <li>Provide opportunities for repeat and spaced practice through assigned work out of class and work during class. Repeat practice spaced over time &mdash; such as having students recall information from earlier in the course &mdash; helps solidify their learning.</li>
      <li>Create opportunities for peer-to-peer learning so that students assist each other in understanding concepts. The basis of quality &ldquo;group work&rdquo; is work that is meaningful for students, in which they can all contribute to each others&rsquo; learning.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Universal design for learning (UDL) is another evidence-based pedagogy approach.UDL is a framework for designing curricula that supports learning for individuals with various needs and learning styles. UDL provides rich supports for learning and reduces barriers to the curriculum while maintaining high achievement standards for all.&rdquo;<sup>15</sup></p>
    <p>UDL guidelines include:<sup>16</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li> Provide multiple means of engagement, which includes providing options for:
        <ul>
          <li>Recruiting interest</li>
          <li>Sustaining effort and persistence</li>
          <li>Self regulation</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Provide multiple means of representation, which includes providing options for:
        <ul>
          <li>Perception</li>
          <li>Language and symbols</li>
          <li>Comprehension</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Provide multiple means of action and expression, which includes providing options for:
        <ul>
          <li>Physical action</li>
          <li>Expression and communication</li>
          <li>Executive functions</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p><a href="http://udlguidelines.cast.org/">Read more about the UDL guidelines</a>.</p>
	<p>To be truly effective, mentors must be attuned to the unique needs of their mentees, including those with specific needs. Providing accommodations is essential for creating a welcoming and supportive mentoring relationship.</p>
	<p>Accommodations are necessary to ensure:</p>
	  <ul>
		  <li>Balanced opportunity: Individuals with specific needs, whether physical, sensory, cognitive, or learning-based, deserve  opportunities for growth and development. Mentors who provide appropriate accommodations help to level the playing field.</li>
	      <li>Accessibility: A mentor’s role is to guide and support. By offering accommodations that remove barriers, mentors ensure their mentees can fully participate in the mentoring process.</li>
	      <li>Success: Accommodations can significantly enhance a mentee's ability to learn, develop new skills, and achieve their goals.</li>
	      <li>Respect and dignity: Offering accommodations demonstrates a mentor's respect for the mentee's individuality and their commitment to creating a welcoming environment.</li>
	      <li>Trust and rapport: When mentors demonstrate a willingness to accommodate their mentee's needs, it fosters trust and builds a strong relationship.</li> </ul>
	  <p>It’s crucial to recognize that accommodations are not one-size-fits-all. Mentors must engage in open and honest conversations with their mentees to identify specific needs and develop tailored solutions.</p>
  </div>
    
            <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-retweet"></i> <strong>9S7.</strong>  Encourage active learning.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Active learning uses instructional activities that involve students in doing things and cause them to think about what they are doing.<sup>17</sup></p>
    <p>This  mode of learning focuses on developing skills rather than transmitting information. Active learning emphasizes higher-order thinking and often involves group work.</p>
    <p><a href="https://cft.vanderbilt.edu/guides-sub-pages/active-learning/">Read more about active learning and active learning techniques</a>.</p>
  </div>
            <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-users"></i> <strong>9S8.</strong>  Facilitate learning in groups.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>One way to facilitate learning in groups with individuals of varying baseline knowledge, skills, and experiences is to use a technique called <em>differentiation</em>. Differentiated instruction gives learners multiple options for taking in information and teaches individuals at their instructional levels.<sup>18</sup></p>
    <p>The following elements compose differentiated instruction:<sup>18</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>High-quality curriculum: Decide what you want learners to <u>know</u>, <u>understand</u>, and be able to <u>do</u> (learning goals) as a result of the learning experience.</li>
      <li>Continual assessment: Continually assess each learner&rsquo;s progress toward the learning goals to help plan the next instructional steps.</li>
      <li>Respectful tasks: Regardless of where learners are in their abilities, learning tasks should be challenging, interesting, and worth doing.</li>
      <li>Building community: Instructors should build a learning community where learners feel safe, accepted, and supported.</li>
      <li>Flexible grouping: Learners work individually, as well as in pairs or groups, with others of the same ability or others of differing abilities, and with the entire class. </li>
      <li>Teaching up: Have all learners work at a level of complexity that is just above their individual comfort levels, so that everyone is challenged.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>For example, an instructor might read from a common text to demonstrate a literary concept, but allow students to select books or articles suitable for their reading levels to apply the concept themselves. </p>
    <p>Assessing students frequently helps instructors determine areas where they need greater support.</p>
    <p><a href="https://www.edutopia.org/topic/differentiated-instruction">Read more about differentiated instruction</a>.</p>
  </div>
            <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-university"></i> <strong>9S9.</strong> Apply  coaching/mentoring for professional development.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p>Mentoring applies to both the here-and-now of a person&rsquo;s career &mdash; immediate tasks and projects that fill a mentee&rsquo;s workdays &mdash; and the development of that individual as a professional.<sup>19</sup></p>
    <p>Opportunities to provide mentorship on career and professional advancement topics may arise organically through the interactions of a mentee and mentor. But they may also require purposeful cultivation.</p>
    <p>Career mentorship focuses on questions such as:<sup>19</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>What do you hope to achieve?</li>
      <li>What kind of setting are you interested in working in?</li>
      <li>Where do you see yourself in five, 10, 20 years?</li>
      <li>What will it take to achieve the vision that you have for yourself?</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Professional advancement mentorship takes a more comprehensive approach, addressing skill sets such as:<sup>19</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li>Writing ability</li>
      <li>Public speaking proficiency</li>
      <li>Professional image</li>
      <li>Networking</li>
      <li>Leadership development</li></ul></div>
              <button class="accordion"><i class="mch-podium"></i> <strong>9S10.</strong> Facilitate opportunities for learners to serve as teachers.</button>
  <div class="panel">
    <p><strong>Moving from Mentee to Mentor</strong></p>
    <p>Those who have enjoyed the benefits of a mentorship in their professional development may desire to become mentors themselves. To succeed as mentors, they will need to develop a skill set consisting of the following abilities:<sup>20</sup></p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Reflection:</strong> Those who are reflective are aware of and continually test their frames of meaning, assumptions, feelings, perceptions, and world-views before acting on them.</li>
      <li><strong>Facilitation:</strong> The ability to share what you know in a way that best fits the moment is a key mentoring skill. Ask questions to promote shared learning, reflective practice, and deeper insight for a mentee.</li>
      <li><strong>Listening:</strong> Listen for silences as well as an understanding of what&rsquo;s being said by a mentee. Read nonverbal cues. Ensure that you balance listening and talking.</li>
      <li><strong>Giving and receiving feedback:</strong> The ability for a mentor to provide honest, constructive feedback to their mentee is a necessary part of a successful mentoring relationship. Elicit feedback from your mentee, focus the feedback you give them on learning and behavior change, not personality. Coach your mentee on how to receive and act on feedback.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>Prospective mentors should consider which of the above attributes they already possess, and what it will take to develop those they do not. </p>
    <p><strong>Pathways to Becoming a Mentor</strong></p>
    <p>Both formal and informal pathways to becoming a mentor exist. </p>
    <p>Sometimes mentees approach prospective mentors of their own volition. In these cases, it&rsquo;s important for the mentor to consider whether there is a suitable fit between what a prospective mentee wants to learn and what skills the mentor possesses.<sup>20</sup></p>
    <p>Occasionally, a mentor sees potential in someone and offers a mentorship opportunity. In these situations, it&rsquo;s important for the prospective mentee to feel they are able to decline the offer without ramifications. Additionally, if the mentee is a direct report, the mentor should consider all the ramifications the new aspect of their relationship will have.<sup>20</sup></p>
    <p>Formal mentorship programs may match mentor with mentee via an algorithm or other mechanism. It&rsquo;s important for a mentor to not read too much into the reason behind the match, and to approach the relationship with an open mind.<sup>20</sup></p>
  </div>
    
  
